qx|B3,General Approach after an Overcall - Major Suit Opening|cs|6|at|
^-{    How to Bid after an Overcall - Major Suit Opening    }
^-|CS||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BHoward: ^*N|cp||at|The important thing to remember is there are now 2 extra bids available to you after your RHO overcalls partner's one of a majors opening. Many bids keep their meaning as if there were no overcall. And the meaning of a few is changed. The two added bids are:|
PG| ***** 1 ***** |


AT|

One is |cp|8|at|double;|cp||at| the other is a |cp|8|at|cue bid|cp||at| of their suit.|
PG| ***** 2 ***** |


AT|

Double as you all know is negative, showing the unbid major. |
PG| ***** 3 ***** |


AT|

A cue bid is a limit+ raise of partner's suit. With minor differences the criteria for cue bid are the same for majors and minors. Because a cue bid is a strong bid, now a jump raise is a weak bid.|
PG| ***** 4 ***** |


AT| So. the auction below:|HT|l|cs|6|at| 
{|ia|,1s2c3s|at|}|HT|m|cs||at|^m@2^Z@33@S does not show a limit raise. If you have a limit raise you bid 3@C. For a limit raise you needs 10+ dummy points. |
PG| ***** 5 ***** |


ht|o|AT|^B@2
 
Bergen raises are off if you play them unless you have prior agreement with partner and they are alertable. Next we illustrate various options. |
PG| ***** 6 ***** |


