^-{    General Approach after an Overcall - Contin.   }
^-|CS||cp|8|AT|

^B@2^*BHoward: ^*N|cp||at|With 10+ points and support for the major bid by the partner you have some choices.|
PG| ***** 13 ***** |


AT|
With 4-card support you always cue bid.|
PG| ***** 14 ***** |


AT|

With 3-card support it is a matter of style. I think more people than not play they can cue bid if they have 10+ points and 3-card support as well as 4-card support. I am  not one of  those people (surprise, lol).|
PG| ***** 15 ***** |


AT|

I think knowing you have a 9-card fit is very important. With the same high cards, a hand with a 9-card fit will usually play a trick better than an 8-card fit. The 9th trump is crucial, because you have more trump available after drawing trump. So, I do not like to cue bid with 3-card support, and will usually bid a new suit first and raise later. |
PG| ***** 16 ***** |


AT|

I play a cue bid promises 4-card support. Occasionally I get stuck and have to lie. But I really like it promising 4-card support. However, If you want to play cue bid shows 3-card support as well, that is fine. ^*BBTW, in competition, New suits by responder are still forcing.^*N|
PG| ***** 17 ***** |


AT|

Let us look at a few related examples.|
PG| ***** 18 ***** |


